---
import PolicyPageLayout from '../../layouts/PolicyPageLayout.astro';

const updatedAt = new Date('2026-07-22');
const sections = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'the-short-version', text: 'The short version' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'when-a-link-is-an-affiliate-link', text: 'When a link is an affiliate link' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'what-a-commission-changes', text: 'What a commission changes' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'what-a-commission-cannot-change', text: 'What a commission cannot change' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'labels-and-link-attributes', text: 'Labels and link attributes' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'tracking-and-third-party-sites', text: 'Tracking and third-party sites' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'sponsorships-and-free-access', text: 'Sponsorships and free access' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'questions', text: 'Questions' },
];
---

<PolicyPageLayout
  title="Affiliate disclosure"
  description="How commercial links may fund evidique, how they are labeled, and what they can never buy."
  kicker="The money note"
  recordLabel="Commercial disclosure"
  {updatedAt}
  {sections}
  highlights={[
    'An affiliate link is treated as commercial only when it is enabled and labeled.',
    'A referral commission should not increase the price you pay.',
    'Money cannot buy a score, category win, or softer criticism.',
  ]}
>
  <h2 id="the-short-version">The short version</h2>
  <p>
    Some evidique pages may link to software vendors through an affiliate program. If you follow a
    clearly labeled affiliate link and complete a qualifying purchase, evidique may receive a
    commission from the vendor.
  </p>
  <p>
    You should not pay more because of that referral. The commission comes from the vendor's
    marketing budget, not an added line on your bill.
  </p>

  <h2 id="when-a-link-is-an-affiliate-link">When a link is an affiliate link</h2>
  <p>
    A product link is not automatically an affiliate link. We treat it as commercial only when the
    affiliate relationship is enabled and the link is labeled on the page. Ordinary editorial links
    may point to the same vendor without generating compensation.
  </p>

  <h2 id="what-a-commission-changes">What a commission changes</h2>
  <p>
    Affiliate revenue may help pay for subscriptions, hosting, and the time required to retest
    software. It can also tell us that readers found a product page useful enough to visit.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the full extent of its editorial role. Revenue is tracked separately from scoring and
    does not become evidence that a product works well.
  </p>

  <h2 id="what-a-commission-cannot-change">What a commission cannot change</h2>
  <p>An affiliate relationship cannot:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>qualify a product for review or guarantee coverage;</li>
    <li>raise a score, create a winner, or remove a documented limitation;</li>
    <li>give a vendor advance approval over a headline, verdict, or comparison;</li>
    <li>prevent us from recommending a non-affiliate alternative.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="labels-and-link-attributes">Labels and link attributes</h2>
  <p>
    Pages that may contain affiliate links include a plain-language disclosure near the relevant
    recommendation or call to action. Enabled commercial links use the appropriate
    <code>rel="sponsored nofollow noopener noreferrer"</code> attributes and open in a new tab.
  </p>
  <p>
    Affiliate destinations are managed centrally so an editor can disable a relationship without
    searching through old articles.
  </p>

  <h2 id="tracking-and-third-party-sites">Tracking and third-party sites</h2>
  <p>
    A vendor or affiliate network may use a referral parameter, cookie, or similar technology after
    you leave evidique. That processing happens under the third party's privacy policy and cookie
    controls. evidique does not receive your payment-card details from those purchases.
  </p>
  <p>
    Review the vendor's price, renewal terms, refund policy, and privacy information before buying.
    Product plans change faster than disclosure pages enjoy admitting.
  </p>

  <h2 id="sponsorships-and-free-access">Sponsorships and free access</h2>
  <p>
    A sponsorship is not the same as an affiliate link. Any paid placement will be labeled as
    sponsored and kept outside editorial rankings. Free or temporary product access will be
    disclosed when it could affect the scope of a test.
  </p>
  <p>
    Neither arrangement guarantees coverage, timing, or a favorable conclusion. The full separation
    rules appear in our <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="questions">Questions</h2>
  <p>
    If a commercial link appears to be missing a label, email
    <a href="mailto:x771364026@gmail.com">x771364026@gmail.com</a> with the page URL and link text.
  </p>
</PolicyPageLayout>
